            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How the Manitoba tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This Manitoba tax calculator estimates your provincial and
                federal income tax based on your total taxable income, basic
                deductions, and non‑refundable tax credits. It is designed for
                individuals who are residents of Manitoba for tax purposes.
              </p>
              <p>
                The tool follows the same general structure as the Canada
                Revenue Agency (CRA) and Manitoba Finance:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Start from your total taxable income.</li>
                <li>
                  Subtract RRSP and other deductions to get
                  <strong>net taxable income</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Apply <strong>federal</strong> and
                  <strong>Manitoba</strong> tax brackets separately.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Subtract basic personal amounts and other non‑refundable
                  credits.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Combine provincial and federal tax to get your total income
                  tax bill.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Formulas used</h2>
              <h3>1. Taxable income</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Taxable income</strong> = Employment &amp; other
                  taxable income − RRSP contributions − Other deductions
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Manitoba provincial tax</h3>
              <p>
                Manitoba uses a progressive tax system. For each bracket, only
                the income within that range is taxed at that bracket’s rate.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  Provincial tax = Σ (Income in bracket <em>i</em> ×
                  Rate<sub>i</sub>) − Provincial non‑refundable credits
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Federal income tax</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  Federal tax = Σ (Income in federal bracket <em>j</em> ×
                  Rate<sub>j</sub>) − Federal non‑refundable credits
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Average and marginal tax rates</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>Average tax rate = Total income tax ÷ Taxable income</p>
                <p>
                  Marginal tax rate ≈ Sum of Manitoba + federal rates in the
                  highest bracket your income reaches
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>5. PST &amp; GST on purchases</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  PST = Purchase amount × PST rate<br />
                  GST = Purchase amount × GST rate<br />
                  Total with tax = Purchase amount + PST + GST
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  The calculator focuses on
                  <strong>employment and general taxable income</strong>, not
                  detailed business, capital gains, or dividend tax rules.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Only the <strong>basic personal amount</strong> and a
                  user‑entered lump sum of other non‑refundable credits are
                  modeled.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It does not compute Canada Child Benefit, GST credit,
                  refundable credits, or Manitoba‑specific rebates.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Bracket thresholds and rates are based on the latest publicly
                  available information but may change with new budgets.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>For official guidance, always refer to:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <a
                    href="https://www.gov.mb.ca/finance/taxation/"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener"
                    >Manitoba Finance – Taxation</a
                  >
                </li>
                <li>
                  <a
                    href="https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency.html"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener"
                    >Canada Revenue Agency (CRA)</a
                  >
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Is Manitoba tax in addition to federal tax?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. As a Manitoba resident, you pay both
                <strong>federal income tax</strong> and
                <strong>Manitoba provincial income tax</strong>. The calculator
                shows each separately and then combines them.
              </p>

              <h3>Does this calculator handle joint income for couples?</h3>
              <p>
                The “Married / common‑law” option lets you enter combined income
                and deductions to get a rough estimate of the household tax.
                However, Canada’s tax system is largely individual, so for
                precise planning you should calculate each spouse’s tax
                separately.
              </p>

              <h3>Are Manitoba tax credits fully modeled?</h3>
              <p>
                No. Manitoba offers a range of credits (e.g., education,
                seniors, property tax credits). This tool lets you enter a
                <strong>total amount of non‑refundable credits</strong> for both
                provincial and federal tax, but it does not compute each credit
                automatically.
              </p>

              <h3>Is this calculator suitable for self‑employed income?</h3>
              <p>
                You can include self‑employment income in the “Employment &amp;
                other taxable income” field, but the calculator does not handle
                CPP contributions, EI premiums, or business‑specific deductions
                in detail. For complex situations, consult a tax professional.
              </p>
